<p>Cornerback, wide receiver, and linebacker are the top three most injured positions by a long shot. It’s no coincidence that the fastest playing players and the ones who tend to take the blunt of each and every hit are the ones falling to these lower body and head injuries.</p>
<p>While the NFL has created rules and invented new technologies to prevent injuries and keep players in the game, it seems they are being out paced by how sped up the league is getting.</p>
<p>The numbers don’t lie, NFL injuries are trending upward, and the league’s countermeasures aren’t working. As the game gets faster and more physical, players’ bodies are paying the price. Rule changes and medical advances have helped, but they can’t overcome basic physics. When elite athletes weighing 250 pounds collide at full speed, something has to give. Until the NFL makes more dramatic changes, things like shorter seasons (which will never happen), mandatory rest periods (like an extra bye week), or fundamental alterations to how the game is played, injuries will continue to climb. For now, fans should get used to seeing their favorite players in street clothes on Sunday. Because in the modern NFL, the question isn’t if a star will get injured, but when.</p>



